  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">A thin single-element THGEM-based, Resistive-Plate WELL (RPWELL) detector was operated with 150 GeV/c muon and pion beams in Ne/(5%CH 4 ), Ar/(5%CH 4 ) and Ar/(7%CO 2 ); signals were recorded with 1 cm 2 square pads and SRS/APV25 electronics. Detection efficiency values greater than 98% were reached in all the gas mixtures, at average pad multiplicity of 1.2. The use of the 10 9 Ω cm resistive plate resulted in a completely discharge-free operation also in intense pion beams. The efficiency remained essentially constant at 98–99% up to fluxes of ∼10 4 Hz/cm 2 , dropping by a few % when approaching 10 5 Hz/cm 2 . These results pave the way towards cost-effective, robust, efficient, large-scale detectors for a variety of applications in future particle, astro-particle and applied fields. A potential target application is digital hadron calorimetry.</subfield>
